Objective: To demonstrate the superiority of scale-invariant logarithmic damping over traditional linear frequency (Hz) damping in modular infrastructure.
​1. Environment Setup
​Software: Any standard Finite Element Analysis (FEA) or CAD suite (SolidWorks, AutoCAD, or OpenFOAM).
​Test Subject: A modular "Hive" structure consisting of 10 interconnected "Puck" nodes.
​Variable Input: Apply a harmonic load (vibration) at the base of the structure.
C_SR = Beta * log10(SR * M)
​M (Magnitude): Set as a dynamic range from 1kg (Puck) to 100,000kg (Vessel).
​SR (Sophisticated Rock): Use the baseline constant of 1.618 (Golden Ratio) for initial kinetic resistance.
​\beta (Distribution): Set to 0.75 to simulate the interconnectedness of the Hive.
​3. Comparative Analysis (The "Bypass" Test)
​Test A (Standard): Run the simulation using a fixed damping coefficient (C = constant). Observe the "Resonance Catastrophe" as M increases.
​Test B (SR Variable): Run the simulation using the logarithmic scaling formula. Observe how the kinetic energy is redistributed through the nodes without structural fatigue.
​4. Expected Results
​Linear Model: Will show structural failure at the transition from Hive to Vessel scale.
​SR Model: Will show a "flat" energy curve, proving that the Ohio Architecture can stabilize a massive structure (The Vessel) using the same logic as a small component (The Puck).
